'''Noussair Mazraoui''' ({{langx|ar|نُصَيْر مَزرَاوِيّ}}; born 14 November 1997) is a professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[Defender (association football)|defender]] for {{English football updater|ManchesU}} club [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] and the [[Morocco national football team|Morocco national team]]. As a versatile player, primarily a right-back, Mazraoui has featured at both [[Full back (association football)|full-back]] positions and at [[centre-back]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.premierleague.com/news/4082862 |title=How Mazraoui and De Ligt will improve Man Utd's defence |publisher=Premier League |date=14 August 2024 |access-date=29 January 2025}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.manutd.com/en/news/detail/ruben-amorim-praises-noussair-mazraoui-as-future-of-manchester-united |title=Amorim praises "future of our team" |publisher=Manchester United F.C. |date=2 December 2024 |access-date=29 January 2025}}</ref>

Mazraoui is a graduate of the [[Ajax Youth Academy]]. He made 137 appearances for the club's first-team, winning three [[Eredivisie]] titles and two [[KNVB Cup]]s. He was signed by [[FC Bayern Munich|Bayern Munich]] in 2022, and won the [[Bundesliga]] title in his debut season. After two seasons with Bayern, he joined Manchester United in August 2024.

Born in the Netherlands, Mazraoui has represented Morocco at youth and senior international level. He has made more than 40 appearances for the senior national team since making his debut in September 2018. He was a member of the Morocco squads that reached the semi-finals of the [[2022 FIFA World Cup]] and won the [[2025 Africa Cup of Nations]].

==Club career==
===Ajax===
[[File:Noussair Mazraoui.jpg|left|thumb|238x238px|Mazraoui with [[AFC Ajax|Ajax]] in 2018]]
Mazraoui grew up in [[Alphen aan den Rijn]] and started playing for local club AVV Alphen at age 4.<ref name="alphen">{{cite news|last1=van der Hansz |first1=Silvester |title=Alphenaar Mazraoui leeft zijn droom tussen de sterren bij Ajax |url=https://www.ad.nl/alphen/alphenaar-mazraoui-leeft-zijn-droom-tussen-de-sterren-bij-ajax~a370278c8/ |work=[[Algemeen Dagblad]] |access-date=5 October 2020 |language=nl |date=30 July 2017}}</ref> He moved to [[Alphense Boys]] three years later, where he only played for a year, before being invited to play in the youth academy of [[AFC Ajax|Ajax]].<ref name="alphen" /> He made his professional debut with Jong Ajax on 12 August 2016 in an [[Eerste Divisie]] game against [[Almere City FC|Almere City]], replacing [[Richairo Živković]] after 86 minutes.<ref name="soccerway2">{{cite web|url=https://int.soccerway.com/matches/2016/08/12/netherlands/eerste-divisie/fc-omniworld/jong-ajax/2240581/|title=Almere City vs. Ajax II – 12 August 2016 – Soccerway|publisher=Soccerway|access-date=24 August 2016}}</ref>

On 4 February 2018, he made his [[Eredivisie]] debut, coming off the bench to substitute [[David Neres]], in a 3–1 victory over [[NAC Breda]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.telegraaf.nl/sport/1628623/tranen-in-aren-a-bij-debuut-ajax-talent |title=Tranen in ArenA bij debuut Ajax-talent |work=De Telegraaf |language=nl |date=5 February 2018 }}</ref> In the following season, on 2 October 2018, he scored his first [[UEFA Champions League|Champions League]] goal in a 1–1 away draw against [[FC Bayern Munich|Bayern Munich]],<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/45645751 |title=Bayern Munich 1–1 Ajax |work=BBC Sport |date=2 October 2018 }}</ref> followed by the only goal in the 92nd minute of stoppage time in a 1–0 victory over [[S.L. Benfica|Benfica]] on 23 October.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.euronews.com/2018/10/23/late-mazraoui-strike-seals-win-for-ajax-over-benfica |title=Late Mazraoui strike seals win for Ajax over Benfica |publisher=Euronews |date=23 October 2018 }}</ref> On 16 December 2018, he netted his first Eredivisie goal in an 8–0 thrashing of [[De Graafschap]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/46586269 |title=Ajax 8–0 De Graafschap |work=BBC Sport |date=16 December 2018 }}</ref> During his breakthrough season, he was named [[List of AFC Ajax records and statistics#AFC Ajax prize winners|Ajax Talent of the Year]], in which he won the domestic double with the club, played in the Champions League semi-finals, and scored four goals in a total of 48 matches.<ref name="auto">{{cite web |url=https://www.bundesliga.com/en/bundesliga/news/noussair-mazraoui-who-is-the-bayern-munich-full-back-ajax-morocco-20082 |title=Noussair Mazraoui: Who is the Bayern Munich and Morocco full-back? |publisher=Bundesliga |date=May 2022 }}</ref>

On 25 October 2020, Mazraoui scored his third [[2020–21 UEFA Champions League|Champions League]] goal in a 3–1 victory against [[FC Midtjylland|Midtjylland]],<ref>{{Cite news |title=Ajax 3–1 FC Midtjylland {{!}} Football |language=en-GB |work=The Guardian |url=https://www.theguardian.com//football/match/2020/nov/25/ajax-v-midtjylland |access-date=7 March 2022 |issn=0261-3077}}</ref> in which Ajax eventually managed to win another domestic double in the 2020–21 season.<ref name="auto"/> In the [[2021–22 UEFA Champions League|2021–22 Champions League]], he was part of the team which won all their six matches in the group stage.<ref name="auto"/> In his last season at Ajax, he managed to score five goals, all in the league, and provide four assists in 35 matches in all competitions.<ref name="auto"/>

===Bayern Munich===
On 24 May 2022, Mazraoui signed a four-year deal with [[FC Bayern Munich|Bayern Munich]], starting from 1 July.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://fcbayern.com/en/news/2022/05/mazraoui-signing |title=FC Bayern sign Noussair Mazraoui |website=Bayern Munich |date=24 May 2022 }}</ref> In January 2023, he had an inflammation in his [[pericardium]] after suffering from [[COVID-19]], which would rule him out for six to eight weeks.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/africa/64187674 |title=Noussair Mazraoui: Bayern Munich defender out with heart inflammation |website=BBC Sport |date=6 January 2023 }}</ref> On 13 May 2023, Mazraoui scored his first goal for the club in a 6–0 home win against [[FC Schalke 04|Schalke 04]] at the [[Allianz Arena]].<ref>{{Cite news |title=Bayern put six past Schalke to move closer to title |language=en-GB |work=BBC Sport |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/65584582 |access-date=2023-05-14}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=Bayern Munich make title statement with dominant win over Schalke |url=https://www.bundesliga.com/en/bundesliga/news/bayern-munich-schalke-live-team-news-match-stats-mane-sane-tuchel-23457 |access-date=2023-05-14 |website=bundesliga.com – the official Bundesliga website |language=en}}</ref>

In October 2023, during the [[Gaza war]], Mazraoui shared a [[Pro-Palestinian]] video via Instagram wishing "victory to our oppressed brothers in [[Palestine]]", which was met with criticism from German [[Bundestag]] member [[Johannes Steiniger]] who demanded his extradition from the country. Furthermore, after backlash within the Bundesliga and Germany MPs, Mazraoui then emphasised that he was against all types of terrorism, hatred and violence.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.deutschlandfunk.de/kritik-an-posting-von-bayern-spieler-mazraoui-zum-nahost-konflikt-100.html |title=Kritik an Posting von Bayern-Spieler Mazraoui zum Nahost-Konflikt |publisher=Deutschlandfunk |language=de |date=16 October 2023 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.br.de/nachrichten/sport/bayern-profi-mazraoui-verbreitet-pro-palaestina-video,TslEKj7 |title=Bayern-Profi Mazraoui verbreitet Pro-Palästina-Video |publisher=br.de |language=de |date=16 October 2023 }}</ref> A few days after Mazraoui's public apology, as well as a personal conversation of him with the club management; Bayern Munich announced that there would be no consequences.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://fcbayern.com/de/news/2023/10/stellungnahme-des-fc-bayern-muenchen-zu-noussair-mazraoui |title=Stellungnahme des FC Bayern München zu Noussair Mazraoui |publisher=FC Bayern Munich |language=de |date=20 October 2023 }}</ref> Following a Champions League match against [[Galatasaray S.K. (football)|Galatasaray]] in Istanbul, the club officials held talks with both Mazraoui and his Bayern Munich Israeli teammate [[Daniel Peretz]]; in addition, the former expressed willingness to meet members of [[:de:Makkabi Deutschland|Makkabi Deutschland]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.sportbuzzer.de/fussball/champions-league/bankett-des-fc-bayern-noussair-mazraoui-an-einem-tisch-mit-daniel-peretz-W7TCTUTJOVBQDDA3ABEYYVSATQ.html |title=Bayern-Bankett: Mazraoui teilt Tisch mit Peretz – Dreesen-Rede mit Ankündigung |publisher=sportbuzzer.de |language=de |date=25 October 2023 }}</ref> A week later, Mazraoui met with representatives of the Jewish Community of Munich and Upper Bavaria, including their President [[Charlotte Knobloch]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.faz.net/aktuell/sport/sportpolitik/noussair-mazraoui-treffen-mit-israelischer-kultusgemeinde-nach-palaestina-posts-19285961.html |title=Reden und schweigen im Fall Mazraoui |work=Frankfurter Allgemeine Zeitung |language=de |date=2 November 2023 }}</ref>

===Manchester United===
On 13 August 2024, Mazraoui signed for [[Premier League]] club [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] on a four-year deal.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.manutd.com/en/news/detail/noussair-mazraoui-signs-for-manchester-united-from-bayern-munich |title=Noussair Mazraoui Signs for United|publisher=Manchester United F.C.|date=13 August 2024 }}</ref> On 16 August, he made his debut in the Premier League and for United in a 1–0 win against [[Fulham F.C.|Fulham]] in the league.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.manutd.com/en/news/detail/match-report-for-man-utd-v-fulham-in-the-premier-league-16-august-2024 |title=Match report: United 1 Fulham 0|publisher=Manchester United F.C.|date=16 August 2024 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Stone |first1=Simon |title=Man Utd 1–0 Fulham: Zirkzee scores late winner on debut as Man Utd beat Fulham in opener |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/live/cr40634rz5wt |website=BBC Sport |access-date=17 August 2024 |date=16 August 2024}}</ref> In October that year, he underwent a minor procedure after experiencing heart [[palpitations]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Stone |first=Simon |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/articles/cwy933kz128o |title=Man Utd's Mazraoui has minor procedure after palpitations |work=BBC Sport |date=10 October 2024 }}</ref> Mazraoui caused some controversy when he refused to wear a rainbow jacket in support of the LGBTQ+ community, citing religious reasons. This caused the club to abandon their plans to wear the jacket.<ref>{{Cite web |date=4 December 2024 |title=Rainbow Laces: Manchester United scrap plans for LGBTQ+ jacket after player refuses to wear it |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/articles/czjd92z22yno |access-date=2024-12-04 |website=BBC Sport |language=en-GB}}</ref>

== Personal life ==
Mazraoui was born in [[Leiderdorp]] in the [[Netherlands]] to Moroccan parents.<ref name="international">{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/45390549 |title=Dutch-born Mazraoui to join up with Morocco for Nations Cup qualifier |website=BBC Sport |date=2 September 2018 |access-date=29 January 2025}}</ref> He is a devout [[Muslims|Muslim]].<ref>{{Cite web |last=zippy86 |date=8 August 2022 |title=Noussair Mazraoui on faith and home as he adjusts to life at Bayern Munich |url=https://www.bavarianfootballworks.com/2022/8/8/23285627/bayern-munich-noussair-mazraoui-transfer-muslim-faith-home-german-sadio-mane-afc-ajax-eredivisie-fcb |access-date=2024-10-03 |website=Bavarian Football Works |language=en}}</ref>

==International career==
Mazraoui was eligible to represent the Netherlands or Morocco at international level.<ref name="international"/> He played youth international football for Morocco at [[Morocco national under-20 football team|under-20]] level.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fff.fr/selection/matchs/167-maroc-france.html |title=Maroc 1–1 France |website=fff.fr |date=8 November 2017 |access-date=29 January 2025}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.besoccer.com/player/matches/n-mazraoui-297669 |title=Mazraoui's matches |website=besoccer.com |access-date=29 January 2025}}</ref> He made his debut for the senior [[Morocco national football team|Morocco national team]] in September 2018, against [[Malawi national football team|Malawi]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://fcbayern.com/en/news/2022/05/this-is-noussair-mazraoui |title=This is Bayern's new signing Noussair Mazraoui |website=fcbayern.com |date=24 May 2022 |access-date=29 January 2025}}</ref>

On 10 November 2021, Mazraoui revealed that the relations between him and Moroccan national team coach [[Vahid Halilhodžić]] fell.<ref>{{Cite web |date=11 November 2021 |title=Vahid and Mazraoui quarreled because of… a bottle! |url=https://www.archysport.com/2021/11/vahid-and-mazraoui-quarreled-because-of-a-bottle/ |access-date=7 March 2022 |website=Archysport |language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=10 November 2021 |title=Maroc : Noussair Mazraoui revient sur son clash avec Vahid Halilhodzic {{!}} Africa Foot United |url=https://africafootunited.com/maroc-noussair-mazraoui-revient-sur-son-clash-avec-vahid-halilhodzic/ |access-date=7 March 2022 |website=africafootunited.com |language=fr-FR |archive-date=5 June 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220605072443/https://africafootunited.com/maroc-noussair-mazraoui-revient-sur-son-clash-avec-vahid-halilhodzic/ |url-status=dead }}</ref> On 13 March 2022, Mazraoui and his Moroccan teammate, [[Hakim Ziyech]], both rejected Halilhodžić's invitation to represent Morocco in the [[2022 FIFA World Cup qualification – CAF third round]] against [[DR Congo national football team|DR Congo]].<ref>{{Cite web |date=13 March 2022 |title=زياش ومزراوي يغيبان عن المنتخب |url=https://www.hespress.com/مزراوي-وزياش-يغيبان-عن-المنتخب-957565.html |access-date=16 March 2022 |website=Hespress – هسبريس جريدة إلكترونية مغربية |language=ar}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=مزراوي يرفض دعوة الإنضمام لمنتخب المغرب |url=https://www.yalla-sport.com/news/348097 |access-date=16 March 2022 |website=yalla-sport.com}}</ref> He later accepted to join the national team and represented Morocco in the 2022 FIFA World Cup after Halilhodžić was replaced by [[Walid Regragui]].

On 10 November 2022, he was named in Morocco's 26-man squad for the [[2022 FIFA World Cup]] in Qatar.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Morocco World Cup 2022 squad: Who's in and who's out? {{!}} Goal.com |url=https://www.goal.com/en-bh/lists/morocco-2022-world-cup-squad-hakimi-ziyech-mazraoui-qatar/blta36257fc4feeb66a |access-date=10 November 2022 |website=Goal (website)}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=10 November 2022 |title=Moroccan coach unveils list of 26 Atlas Lions in 2022 World Cup |url=https://en.hespress.com/52697-moroccan-coach-unveils-list-of-26-atlas-lions-in-2022-world-cup.html |access-date=10 November 2022 |website=HESPRESS English – Morocco News |language=en-US}}</ref> He played a big role in Morocco's charge to the semi-finals, helping them become the first African side to reach this stage at a World Cup.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bundesliga.com/en/bundesliga/news/morrocans-2022-world-cup-achraf-hakimi-noussair-mazraoui-22055 |title=Moroccans in the Bundesliga, including 2022 World Cup bronze medal challengers Achraf Hakimi and Noussair Mazraoui |website=Bundesliga |date=16 December 2022 }}</ref>

On 28 December 2023, Mazraoui was among the 27 players selected by coach Walid Regragui to represent Morocco in the [[2023 Africa Cup of Nations]].<ref>{{Cite web |date=28 December 2023 |title=Regragui unveils 27 player list for Morocco's participation in CAN 2023 |url=https://en.hespress.com/77181-regragui-unveils-27-player-list-for-moroccos-participation-in-can-2023.html |access-date=2023-12-29 |website=HESPRESS English – Morocco News |language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=28 December 2023 |title=Regragui names 27 provisional players for AFCON |url=https://www.cafonline.com/caf-africa-cup-of-nations/news/regragui-names-27-provisional-players-for-afcon/ |access-date=2023-12-29 |website=CAF |language=en-GB}}</ref> He was also included in the squad called up for the same tournament in the 2025 edition. Competing on home soil as the host nation, Mazraoui helped Morocco advance to the final, where they faced [[Senegal national football team|Senegal]]. In the final match, Morocco failed to secure the championship and had to concede defeat to their opponents, with Senegal winning by a score of 1–0.<ref>{{Cite web|date=19 January 2026 |title=Player protests, an awful penalty and fan uproar: What happened in the most chaotic AFCON final in history |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2026/01/19/sport/soccer-afcon-senegal-morocco-final-chaos |access-date=2026-03-03 |website=BBC |language=en}}</ref> However, in March 2026, the result was overturned due to Senegal walking off the pitch to protest a refereeing decision, handing Morocco the title.<ref name=":0">{{Cite news |last=Bosher |first=Luke |last2=Joseph |first2=Sam |last3=Harris |first3=Jay |date=2026-03-18 |title=Morocco crowned AFCON winners 57 days after final as Senegal's victory declared void |url=https://www.nytimes.com/athletic/7126755/2026/03/17/afcon-morocco-senegal-final-overturned/ |access-date=2026-03-18 |work=The New York Times |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331}}</ref>

